snippet.textDisplay:
She suffered unexpected trauma when captured.. she walked over to the food in trust and in need to eat.
..and she felt terribly let down by the capture even before she could even taste that needed food.

She was disappointed to the extent by the acts of humans that she not only surrendered, she turned herself off to a mushy state, feeling totally helpless!

Capturing her like that (and it has to be done in order to help the animals) wasn't lovely at all.

She was now expecting only worse to follow, and there was only one thing she had left to do.. to disappear in that corner, the humans had bullied her into!

Experiencing 'loss of freedom' is horrifying.

It took months for her natural instincts to synthesise to being somewhat normal again!

We hope & pray that captures for one reason or another be much more considerate in the future as we develop our existing methods,, and also gain more insights into the psychology of these dependant life forms like us life forms, with the difference of humans being independent & controlling, the existing practices of help, medical, and food & shelter must improve.

It's devastating watching shelter animals (on adoption days) trying so hard to get away from there.. it must be horrible (from animals point of view) living in the shelter seeing & watching other traumatised/abused animals being brought in all the time.
It must be depressing to say the least.

For one thing, there's much needed govt/NGO support required to move all these shelters to the outskirts, and leave only the initial contact medical assessment & help where they are.
Rescued animals need open space to heal physically & emotionally.. they need to run around in the open in order to put the past behind.
Instead they find themselves narrowly caged right next to one another listening to screaming of dark torturous narratives .

Also now that they feel a bit better after the initial medical help, food & a bath, they want to stretch out, and not be locked away in shelters that are more like trauma hubs for these poor souls who are unable to appreciate the complex human methods of help. Soon as they feel a bit better, they want to feel free on own to choose in own time & 'space'.

In the meantime, God bless the people who are helping, paid or unpaid. They go much out of their way to help!

Best regards
